l that paradoxically engages South Africa’s crucial social and political problems by, in fact, seeming to ignore them. Politicians and cultural critics have long criticized kwaito for failing to provide any meaningful contribution to a society that desperately needs direction. As Steingo shows, however, these criticisms are built on problematic assumptions about the political function of music. Interacting with kwaito artists and fans, he shows that youth aren’t escaping their social condition through kwaito but rather using it to expand their sensory realities and generate new possibilities. Resisting the truism that “music is always political,” Steingo elucidates a music that thrives on its radically ambiguous relationship with politics, power, and the state.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aKwaito (Music)xPhilosophy and aesthetics. 0aKwaito (Music)xPolitical aspects. 0aKwaito (Music)xSocial aspects. 0aMusicians, BlackzSouth Africa. 7aMUSIC / General.2bisacsh  amusic, musical, musician, aesthetic, aesthetics, freedom, justice, south africa, african, 1990s, contemporary, modern, 20th century, apartheid, nelson mandela, history, historical, government, elections, president, urban, black, youth, young people, electronic, electronica, genre, generational, attitude, outlook, injustice, social studies, poverty, crime, wealth, society.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311071098440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226362687423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226362687/original  a978-3-11-071098-4  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles